# Xiaomi Mi Fitness — Health Data Exporter

[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](LICENSE)
[![Python 3.9+](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.9%2B-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/)
[![Status: tested](https://img.shields.io/badge/status-tested%20%E2%9C%93-success.svg)](#)
[![PRs welcome](https://img.shields.io/badge/PRs-welcome-brightgreen.svg)](#contributing--contact)
[![Research use](https://img.shields.io/badge/built%20for-medical%20research-9cf.svg)](#contributing--contact)

Download **your own Xiaomi Mi Band / Mi Watch health data** (sleep, heart rate, SpO₂, steps,
calories…) straight to your computer as CSV files, by automating Xiaomi's official **GDPR
"Download a copy"** export. Works for a **single account** (a friendly CLI where you type your
e-mail) or in **bulk** for **dozens of accounts**, organising everything into folders named by
acquisition date.

> ✅ **Tested and working** on real Xiaomi accounts (Mi Band 10 / Mi Fitness) in June 2026.
> Built and used by a **respiratory-medicine research group** to make wearable-data collection
> for clinical studies reproducible. If you want to collaborate or need help, write to
> **elarfaouiwasim@gmail.com**.

---

## Why this exists

The Mi Band / Mi Watch have **no public data API**: the watch syncs to **Xiaomi's cloud** (Mi
Fitness), and the only complete way to get *all* your data out is the **GDPR export** in
Xiaomi's privacy portal. Done by hand it is slow (log in → e-mail code → request → wait for a
second e-mail → download → decrypt). This tool automates that end to end, so you can get your
data with one command — and researchers can do it for a whole cohort.

**Important:** the export reflects **what is in the Xiaomi cloud**, which only has data if the
**Mi Fitness app** synced your watch. If a watch is unpaired / the app is closed, the export
will be empty or stale even if the watch was worn.

---

## How it works (the real Xiaomi flow)

1. **Log in** to your Mi account (e-mail + password + a 6-digit code sent to your e-mail).
2. Open **Privacy → Manage your data → MI Fitness → “Download a copy”** (this step asks for a
   second code, and the button has a short countdown you must confirm).
3. Xiaomi prepares the file and **e-mails you a download link + a password**. This can take
   from a few minutes up to **15 working days**; the link is valid for **7 days**.
4. The link opens a page where you click **“File #1”** to download an **AES-encrypted ZIP**.
5. The tool **decrypts** it with the password from the e-mail and **extracts the CSVs**.

Two things need a human or your inbox:
- **Captcha:** Xiaomi shows a slide captcha on new logins → run with a **visible window** and
  solve it once per account (the session is then remembered).
- **Verification codes:** either you **type them** (`--otp manual`, no e-mail setup) or the
  tool **reads them from your inbox over IMAP** (`--otp imap`, handy for bulk).

---

## Install

```bash
git clone https://github.com/WElArfaoui/xiaomi-health-exporter.git
cd xiaomi-health-exporter
python3 -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e .                 # installs deps + the `xiaomi-export` command
python -m playwright install chromium
```

After `pip install -e .` you can use the short command `xiaomi-export ...` anywhere instead of
`python -m xiaomi_export ...` (both work).

---

## Use it — single account (the easy way)

You type the codes yourself; no e-mail credentials needed.

```bash
# 1) Request your data copy (a browser opens: solve the captcha, type the e-mailed code)
python -m xiaomi_export request --email you@example.com

# 2) When Xiaomi e-mails you the download link + password, run:
python -m xiaomi_export download --email you@example.com \
    --url "https://tools.privacy.mi.com/userRight/downloadPrivacyInfo?...&productId=MiWear" \
    --password-zip "PasswordFromTheEmail"
```

Your data lands in `./xiaomi_data/you/you_DDMMYYYY/` as CSV files.

---

## Use it — many accounts (bulk, for research cohorts)

Put the accounts in a CSV (see `examples/accounts.example.csv`):

```csv
email,password,imap_password,label
watch01@example.com,XiaomiPass1,,watch01
watch02@example.com,XiaomiPass2,MailboxPass2,watch02
```

Then let it read the verification codes and download links automatically over IMAP:

```bash
# First login of each account needs the captcha solved once (visible window):
python -m xiaomi_export request  --accounts accounts.csv --otp imap --imap-host mail.example.com

# Later (the e-mails may take a while), download everything that is ready:
python -m xiaomi_export download --accounts accounts.csv --otp imap --imap-host mail.example.com
```

Each account is saved to `./xiaomi_data/<label>/<label>_<DDMMYYYY>/`, so re-running on a
later date keeps a dated history per watch. Re-run `download` periodically until all arrive
(the link is valid 7 days).

---

## Options

| Option | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `--email` / `--accounts` | one account, or a CSV of many |
| `--otp manual\|imap` | type the codes yourself, or read them from IMAP |
| `--imap-host` / `--imap-port` | IMAP server (for `--otp imap`) |
| `--output-dir` | where to save data (default `./xiaomi_data`) |
| `--headful` / `--headless` | show the browser (default) or hide it (only if no captcha) |
| `--gap` | seconds between accounts in bulk |
| `--skip-done` | (request) skip accounts already requested |

---

## Output

```
xiaomi_data/<label>/
├── <label>_DDMMYYYY.zip          # the encrypted ZIP (kept)
└── <label>_DDMMYYYY/             # decrypted CSVs
    ├── ..._hlth_center_fitness_data.csv   # the bulk health data (HR, SpO2, sleep, steps, ...)
    ├── ..._hlth_center_sport_record.csv
    └── ...
```

The main file `hlth_center_fitness_data.csv` has a `Key` column that separates each metric
(`heart_rate`, `spo2`, `sleep`, `steps`, `calories`, …), a `Time` (Unix timestamp) and a JSON
`Value`.

---

## Security & privacy

- This tool runs **entirely on your machine**; your credentials and data never leave it.
- Treat `accounts.csv` as a secret (it holds passwords). It is git-ignored by default.
- Sessions and downloaded data are git-ignored too.
- Use it only with **accounts you own / are authorised to access**.

---

## Notes & limits

- **Rate limit:** requesting codes too many times for the *same* account triggers
  “Too many frequent attempts” — wait a while.
- **Captcha** can appear on the download login too if your IP has done a lot of logins; just
  solve it in the window.
- The data you get is whatever the **Mi Fitness app synced to the cloud** — check the dates in
  the CSVs to confirm the watch is actually syncing.

